      <h1>Kenya Payroll REST API Documentation</h1>

      <section>
        <h2>Overview</h2>
        <p>
          The Kenya Payroll REST API enables developers to calculate statutory
          payroll deductions and net salary using the latest Kenyan payroll
          rules. It provides a simple JSON endpoint for integrating payroll
          calculations into HR systems, accounting software, ERP platforms,
          payroll applications, and custom business solutions. The API supports
          calculations for PAYE (Pay As You Earn), NSSF contributions, SHIF
          contributions, Housing Levy, taxable income, and net salary. Responses
          are returned in a consistent JSON format, making the API easy to
          integrate with web, mobile, and backend applications. Designed with a
          RESTful architecture, the API uses standard HTTP methods and JSON
          payloads, allowing you to perform payroll calculations without
          implementing complex tax logic in your own application. As statutory
          rates change, the API can be updated so your integrations continue
          using current calculation rules. Whether you're building a payroll
          system, employee self-service portal, salary calculator, or financial
          application, the Kenya Payroll REST API provides a reliable and
          straightforward way to automate Kenyan payroll calculations.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Authentication</h2>
        <p>
          The API is currently publicly accessible and does not require
          authentication.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Note:</strong> Authentication (such as API keys or Bearer
          tokens) may be introduced in a future release. If this occurs, advance
          notice and updated documentation will be provided to help existing
          integrations migrate smoothly.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Endpoints</h2>
        <p>
          The Kenya Payroll REST API is versioned to ensure backward
          compatibility as new features, calculation rules, and improvements are
          introduced.
        </p>

        <p>
          The API currently exposes a single endpoint. Different payroll
          calculations are selected by specifying a
          <strong>serviceCode</strong> in the request body. This approach
          provides a consistent interface while allowing multiple payroll
          services to be accessed through the same endpoint.
        </p>

        <h3>Base Endpoint</h3>
        <pre><code>/api/v1/</code></pre>

        <h3>Calculator endpoint</h3>
        <pre><code>/api/v1/calculator</code></pre>

        <p></p>

        <p>
          Requests are sent to the base endpoint using the
          <code>POST</code> method. The required payroll calculation is
          determined by the <code>serviceCode</code> field in the JSON request
          body.
        </p>

        <h3>Available Endpoint Methods</h3>

        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Method</th>
              <th>Description</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><code>POST</code></td>
              <td>
                Calculates payroll deductions based on the supplied
                <code>serviceCode</code> and request data.
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Available Service Codes</h3>

        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Service Code</th>
              <th>Description</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><code>NETPAY</code></td>
              <td>
                Calculates PAYE, NSSF, SHIF, Housing Levy, taxable income, total
                statutory deductions, and net salary.
              </td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><code>NSSF</code></td>
              <td>
                Calculates employee and employer NSSF contributions based on the
                supplied gross salary. <strong>NOTE:</strong> The returned
                contribution represents the amount payable by each party
                (employee and employer).
              </td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><code>SHIF</code></td>
              <td>
                Calculates the Social Health Insurance Fund (SHIF) contribution
                based on the supplied gross salary.
              </td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><code>HOUSINGLEVY</code></td>
              <td>
                Calculates employee and employer Housing Levy contributions
                based on the supplied gross salary.
              </td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><code>PAYE</code></td>
              <td>
                Calculates PAYE (Pay As You Earn) tax based on the supplied
                taxable income and applicable tax reliefs.
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <p>
          All requests must include the following
          <strong>HTTP header:</strong><br />

          <code>Content-Type: application/json</code>
        </p>

        <p>
          Every request must also include a valid
          <strong>serviceCode</strong> in the JSON request body. Refer to the
          service code table above for the list of supported values.
        </p>

        <p>
          The endpoint accepts a JSON request body and returns a JSON response.
        </p>

        <p>
          All successful responses are returned in JSON format with an
          appropriate HTTP status code.
        </p>

        <p>
          The following sections provide request and response examples for each
          supported
          <code>serviceCode</code>.
        </p>
      </section>

